So for kubernetes by dafault path based routing will not be supported by load balancer 


KUbernetes INGRESS : 
By Default Kubernetes created loadbalancer run on layer-4 so which is not support path base routings 
so if we want to deploy multiple application to route to common loadn balancer we have ti use ingress controller to support
path based routing 


🚦 Kubernetes Service vs Ingress (Correct Concept)
1. Default Kubernetes Service (LoadBalancer / NodePort)

When you expose an app using:

NodePort
LoadBalancer

It works at Layer 4 (TCP/UDP)

What Layer 4 means:
Works on IP + Port
❌ Does NOT understand HTTP paths like /app1, /app2
❌ Cannot do host-based routing like app1.example.com

Example:

http://LB-IP:30001 → App A
http://LB-IP:30002 → App B

So yes:
✔ It cannot do path-based routing
✔ It is not application-aware (HTTP unaware)

2. Kubernetes Ingress (Solution)

Ingress works at Layer 7 (HTTP/HTTPS)

It allows:

✔ Path-based routing
/app1 → service-a
/app2 → service-b
✔ Host-based routing
app1.example.com → service-a
app2.example.com → service-b
3. Important Correction in your statement

You said:

“Kubernetes created loadbalancer run on layer-4 so which is not support path base routings”

✔ Correct idea
❗ But more precise wording:

Kubernetes Service LoadBalancer is a Layer 4 abstraction provided by cloud provider, and it does not provide HTTP routing capabilities.

4. Why Ingress Controller is needed

Ingress is NOT a load balancer by itself.

You must install an Ingress Controller, such as:

NGINX Ingress Controller
AWS ALB Ingress Controller
Traefik
HAProxy
Flow:
Internet
   ↓
AWS Load Balancer (L4 or L7 depending setup)
   ↓
Ingress Controller (NGINX/ALB)
   ↓
Kubernetes Services
   ↓
Pods
5. Real-world example
Without Ingress:

You need multiple LoadBalancers:

LB1 → App1
LB2 → App2
LB3 → App3

💸 Expensive + messy

With Ingress:
Single LB
   ├── /app1 → App1
   ├── /app2 → App2
   └── /app3 → App3

✔ Cheaper
✔ Clean routing
✔ Industry standard

6. Final corrected version of your statement

You can write it like this:

By default, Kubernetes Services like LoadBalancer operate at Layer 4 (TCP/UDP) and do not support application-level routing 
such as path-based or host-based routing. To enable advanced HTTP routing for multiple applications using a single load balancer,
we use an Ingress Controller, which operates at Layer 7 and routes traffic based on URL paths or hostnames\


